10. Repeat the previous step with another link if necessary, until you find the most useful resource.
I understand you want me to perform a web search. I'll execute these steps using Firefox and navigate through the search results.

   123	
   124	When people encounter the word cannabis, they often think of
   125	the dried greenish-to-brownish product of the plant, usually called
   126	marijuana, pot or weed.
   127	But cannabis can be used to make a wide range of products that
   128	differ in their:
   129	•
   130	
   131	Appearance and consistency
   132	
   133	•
   134	
   135	Taste and smell
   136	
   137	•
   138

   140

   144

   147	Method of use
   148	
   149	Cannabis products belong in one of three categories:
   150	1.
   151	
   152	Dried cannabis
   153	
   154	2.
   155	
   156	Cannabis extracts
   157	
   158	3.
   159	
   160	Edible cannabis or edibles
   161	
   162	Each type of cannabis product may have different benefits, and pose
   163	different health and safety risks.
   164	Cannabis topicals are a fourth category, but since they do not present
   165	the risks and harms of the other categories, they will not be covered
   166	in this guide.
   167	
   168	THC (tetrahydrocannabinol) is the primary component of cannabis
   169	that produces the high. The potency of cannabis depends on how
   170	much THC it contains.
   171	CBD (cannabidiol) does not produce a high but can cause drowsiness.
   172	CBD is being researched for its potential medical application.

   182	While many strains of cannabis exist, including sativa, indica and
   183	hybrid, research shows that different strains do not produce different
   184	effects. A more important indicator of effects are the levels of THC
   185	and CBD.
   186	The more THC in a product the greater the risk of experiencing

   256	 Inhaling Compared to

   258	Whether cannabis is inhaled or ingested will influence when
   259	and for how long the effects (the high) of cannabis are felt.
   260	
   261	Cannabis:
   262	
   263	Inhaling vs Ingesting
   264	To lower your risk of the harmful effects of cannabis, you need to understand
   265	the differences between the two most common ways of consuming it.
   266	
   267	INHALING
   268	
   269	— eating or drinking —
   270	
   271	Cannabis smoke or vapour delivers THC,
   272	the chemical that gets you high, into
   273	your lungs where it passes directly into
   274	your bloodstream and then your brain.
   275	
   276	Edible cannabis travels first to your stomach then to
   277	your liver before getting into your bloodstream and
   278	brain. The liver converts THC into a stronger form
   279	and this combined with the THC from the original
   280	product adds to the intensity of the high.
   281	
   282	You will feel the effects
   283	from seconds to
   284	a few minutes of inhaling.
   285	Full effects can peak
   286	within 30 minutes.
   287	Effects can last up to 6 hours
   288	after use. Some residual effects
   289	can last up to 24 hours.

   292

   294

   296

   307	You will feel effects
   308	within 30 minutes to
   309	2 hours of ingesting.
   310	Full effects can peak
   311	within 4 hours.
   312	Effects can last up to 12 hours

   314	can last up to 24 hours.
   315	
   316	 The Spectrum of Cannabis Use
   317	Cannabis use, like the use of alcohol and other substances, exists on a
   318	spectrum. This means that cannabis use can be different for everyone at any
   319	given time. Anyone can move back and forth along the spectrum in
   320	their lifetime.
   321	Consider the information below and think about where you might fit. This is
   322	not a diagnosis. It is just meant to help you reflect on your cannabis use.
   323	
   324	1. Abstinence
   325	
   326	Choosing to abstain from or not use cannabis to avoid all health
   327	risks or for other personal reasons
   328	Example: A person who has chosen to never begin using cannabis
   329	or who has quit using cannabis.
   330	
   331	2. Beneficial Use
   332	
   333	Use that might have some positive impact, either physically, mentally,
   334	socially or spiritually
   335	Example: A person who has been authorized to use cannabis for
   336	medical purposes by a healthcare provider.
   337	
   338	3. Non-Problematic Use
   339	
   340	Cannabis use that might have negligible health and social impacts
   341	Example: A person who uses cannabis occasionally (e.g., weekly or
   342	less) and follows the Lower-Risk Cannabis Use Guidelines
   343	(see page 11)
   344	
   345	4. Problematic Use
   346	
   347	Cannabis use that begins to affect a person’s health and interferes
   348	with their school, work, family, social or financial responsibilities
   349	Example: A person who continues to use cannabis daily or almost
   350	daily despite the negative impact on their mental or physical health.
   351	
   352	5. Cannabis Use Disorder
   353	
   354	Cannabis use that has led to dependence or addiction to cannabis
   355	Example: A person who has persistent cravings for cannabis
   356	and has a hard time reducing or controlling their cannabis use
   357	(see page 8).

   596	 Cannabis Use Disorder
   597	Cannabis is an addictive substance and people who use cannabis
   598	can become dependent on it. Cannabis dependence is medically
   599	known as cannabis use disorder. A cannabis use disorder can be
   600	mild, moderate or severe.
   601	Signs and symptoms of cannabis use disorder include:
   602	•
   603	
   604	Using more cannabis than planned
   605	
   606	•
   607	
   608	Trying unsuccessfully to control use
   609	
   610	•
   611

   613	cannabis or recovering from its effects

   619	•
   620

   622	because of cannabis use
   623	
   624	•
   625

   627	recreational activities because of cannabis use
   628	
   629	•
   630	
   631	Continuing use despite recurring physical or
   632	psychological problems caused by cannabis
   633	
   634	•
   635

   637	relationships
   638	
   639	•
   640	
   641	Using cannabis in physically dangerous situations
   642

   644

   646

   648

   650	disorders, anxiety, aggression, decreased appetite, weight
   651	loss and restlessness
   652	
   653	•
   654	
   655	Other withdrawal symptoms include sweating, stomach

   667	 Cannabis Use and Your Health
   668	Regular cannabis use can lead to dependence or a cannabis use
   669	disorder. Regular use refers to weekly or more frequent cannabis
   670	use for long periods of time (i.e., months to years).
   671	But you don’t have to be dependent on cannabis to experience
   672	health problems. Using cannabis regularly can:
   673	•
   674	
   675	Affect your concentration, memory and decision
   676	making
   677	
   678	•
   679	
   680	Interfere with your work or school, family and social
   681	responsibilities
   682	
   683	•
   684

   686	
   687	•
   688	
   689	Increase your risk of developing psychosis and
   690	schizophrenia
   691	
   692	•
   693	
   694	Can affect how the brain develops, especially if you start
   695	using cannabis at a young age before the brain has fully
   696	developed
